WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:20.000
3 2 1 and action.

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:24.000
Today is Saturday, March 9, 2013.

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:33.000
My name is Dr. Hasan Kwame Jeffries at the Ohio State University and the Southern oral history program at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:52.000
I'm with videographer Petna Dalico in Albany, Georgia on the campus of Albany State University to conduct an interview for the Civil Rights History Project, which is a joint undertaking of the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture and the Library of Congress.

00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:58.000
We are here with Johnnie Ruth Brawner McCullar.

00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:04.000
Thank you so much for being here with us to share your story.

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:09.000
I'd like to begin just by asking you where you were born.

00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:13.000
I was born in Terrell County, in Sasser, Georgia, Georgia.

00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:18.000
And you were born February 4, 1940.

00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:20.000
And your parents? What were their names?

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:23.000
Clifford Brawner and Johnnie Lou Brawner.

00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:28.000
And they, too, were from the area. They were from Southwest.

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:30.000
Yes. Georgia.

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:38.000
Yes. How far back did your family have roots in Sasser, Georgia?

00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:50.000
My father's parents moved here from Worth County, which is a few miles from Terrell County. the line sort of meets.

00:01:50.000 --> 00:02:05.000
My mother, I don't quite know. I understand from her that her family originated from some parts of Alabama when I don't know.

00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:09.000
What was your mother like? In her youth while you were growing up?

00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:15.000
I tried to buy it, always working.

00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:26.000
She was always looking for something to do, canning, sewing, making quilts, always something to make sure the family had what they did.

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:28.000
And how about your father?

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:34.000
He was a hard worker. He was first, he was a farmer.

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:41.000
We moved off the farm in the 50s. I don't remember exactly what year.

00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:50.000
He worked for a while at the Marine Base. And from there to the...

00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:54.000
fertilizer plant, I can't remember the name Swift. That's the name of...

00:02:54.000 --> 00:02:55.000
Down here.

00:02:55.000 --> 00:03:00.000
And Albany, Georgia, yes. He retired from there after about 28 years.

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:03.000
Do you remember life on farm?

00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:06.000
I didn't like it.

00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:11.000
What was it about the life on farm that you did?

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:17.000
Well, I was afraid of all the animals. I didn't like the heat.

00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:22.000
I didn't like the mosquitoes, I didn't like the gnats, all that other stuff.

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:28.000
And I was afraid of snakes. Very afraid of snakes.

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:30.000
Why not have you about that?

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:33.000
Now where was the farm located?

00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:36.000
Oh goodness.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:41.000
Down floor to shore, back in the area near...

00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:45.000
It's a place called Dubgaate, back in that area.

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:48.000
Of Old Dawson Road.

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:55.000
And when your family left the farm, where did they move?

00:03:55.000 --> 00:03:58.000
To Sassar, which is in the city of Limson, Sassar.

00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:01.000
Now they're all home, I was asked.

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:03.000
You like Sassar more?

00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:04.000
Yes.

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:08.000
What was it about Sassar that was more appealing to you?

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:10.000
Not a whole lot of snakes.

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:13.000
Because it wasn't the farm.

00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:14.000
No farm.

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:16.000
What was life like for you?

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:20.000
But then you were 12, 13?

00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:21.000
Yes.

00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:27.000
How did life change for you when you moved to Sassar?

00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:33.000
I can't say that it was better because we always had a good life.

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:37.000
We had what we needed. We was always full.

00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:41.000
We had the clothing that we needed because my mother was a good seamstress.

00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:44.000
So she made that clothing.

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:50.000
I can't say it was in a better way to move there than when we were on the farm.

00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:54.000
It's just that I didn't have to do the farm work.

00:04:54.000 --> 00:04:59.000
What was your responsibility while you were on that farm?

00:04:59.000 --> 00:05:07.000
Oh, faith in chickens, milk the cow, which I was afraid of.

00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:10.000
Sometimes I had to pick cotton.

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:13.000
I didn't very good at that.

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:18.000
So I really, I really, really, to be fair, I didn't do too much on the farm.

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:24.000
But what the little bit I did I wanted to have you about.

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:31.000
When you were working that didn't, we had talked to your brother a little earlier, Clif.

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:35.000
And he was saying that he didn't have to and didn't record whether or not his siblings had to.

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:40.000
So you were work instead of going to school.

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:43.000
We would work when we weren't in school.

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:44.000
Okay.

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:47.000
When it was time to go to school, we went to school.

00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:50.000
How long was the school year?

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:53.000
School was always out in April.

00:05:53.000 --> 00:05:59.000
It usually was start in October.

00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:06.000
And so in that in between time, spring, summer, into early fall, you'll be helping out on the farm.

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:08.000
Yeah, what I could do, yes.

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:11.000
Do you remember the elementary school that you had gone to?

00:06:11.000 --> 00:06:14.000
One room school.

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:17.000
The name of it was Panty Grove.

00:06:17.000 --> 00:06:19.000
Panty Grove.

00:06:19.000 --> 00:06:22.000
Do you remember the name of your teacher?

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:28.000
My first teacher's name was Vanny Wakefield, I believe.

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:33.000
And what was it like going to that one room school, Panty Grove?

00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:35.000
It was fun.

00:06:35.000 --> 00:06:40.000
Seven grades in one building, one teacher.

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:44.000
About how many students are we talking about?

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:50.000
Maybe about 40, a less.

00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:56.000
And this is, do you stay in Panty Grove for how many years?

00:06:56.000 --> 00:07:00.000
I think I was six grade when we left.

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:02.000
And then you had to wear?

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:04.000
To Sassar, to Dunbar.

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:05.000
Okay, to Dunbar.

00:07:05.000 --> 00:07:06.000
And that's the middle school?

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:13.000
That was elementary school that went from first grade through ninth grade.

00:07:13.000 --> 00:07:18.000
And was that experience different than going to Panty Grove?

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:20.000
Yes.

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:25.000
Was it all in one grade to a classroom?

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:30.000
And then from there you had to high school.

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:31.000
High school.

00:07:31.000 --> 00:07:32.000
And what high school did you attend?

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:33.000
Carver High School.

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:34.000
And where was Carve?

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:35.000
In Dawson.

00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:36.000
In Dawson.

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:38.000
Yes.

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:42.000
What was Carve a life?

00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:46.000
Well, it was an experience being in high school.

00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:53.000
I met a lot of other people that I didn't know.

00:07:53.000 --> 00:07:57.000
It was cold, both at the time, with one heater in the classroom.

00:07:57.000 --> 00:08:00.000
You had your sitting classroom with your heavy coats on.

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:05.000
You know, or to stay warm.

00:08:05.000 --> 00:08:09.000
There was no lunch room, so you had to carry your lunch.

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:15.000
If you had a lunch, you would take your lunch room home.

00:08:15.000 --> 00:08:22.000
Well, it wasn't what it should have been.

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:26.000
We didn't have the equipment that we needed.

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:31.000
There were two classes, and that was a divide of between the two classrooms.

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:36.000
So when we had, and it was used for an auditorium,

00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:41.000
whenever we had some type of program, they had to remove the petition

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:45.000
from between the two classrooms.

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:50.000
And you could hear what was going on in the other classroom.

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:54.000
So it was kind of, sometimes we kind of know as it.

00:08:54.000 --> 00:08:57.000
And so this is the mid-1950s?

00:08:57.000 --> 00:08:58.000
Yes.

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:02.000
1954 and 1950s.

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:06.000
End of 55, 56.

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:08.000
Is when you start?

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:10.000
When I started 10th grade.

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:14.000
Now, you know, the famous Brown ruling,

00:09:14.000 --> 00:09:16.000
Stagnath's segregation and education,

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:20.000
as unconstitutional, had been passed two years earlier.

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:26.000
Was there any talk about desegregating schools at that time while you were in school?

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:30.000
No, because at that time, like people,

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:36.000
seemed to be in afraid to really discuss stuff like that.

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:41.000
If my member serves me right,

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:49.000
there was certain amount of information that you could get from government.

00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:55.000
The black teachers, I think, were told what to teach.

00:09:55.000 --> 00:09:58.000
So, you know, we didn't know too much about government.

00:09:58.000 --> 00:10:00.000
How about that home?

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:04.000
Was it where any conversations or discussions of the sort?

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:09.000
My parents didn't know too much about segregation or, you know, about end of schools.

00:10:09.000 --> 00:10:15.000
But they knew that we didn't have what we needed in order to be properly educated.

00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:18.000
The books were pages were torn out.

00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:21.000
We were getting them from the white schools.

00:10:21.000 --> 00:10:22.000
They got new books.

00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:25.000
They were passing old ones down to us.

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:33.000
There would be writings all over the books and pages, part of the pages, are torn out.

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:37.000
Sometimes, we would have one spelling book to a class.

00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:44.000
The teacher would have to put the words on the board and you would have to write them off.

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:47.000
Because they didn't have enough books.

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:54.000
Did you ever talk to your mother or father about the way things were?

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:57.000
I don't recall.

00:10:57.000 --> 00:11:01.000
How about friends?

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:02.000
Classmates.

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:12.000
We complained about having to take so many minutes out of the classroom and evening classes to clean up the buildings.

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:16.000
Because we had no gender or your sisters.

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:19.000
And so that responsibility for all of you all of us?

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:20.000
Yes.

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:21.000
And all of us.

00:11:21.000 --> 00:11:28.000
They put down the dust compound, but it was still dusty.

00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:35.000
So you spend your four years in high school and you graduate in 1959?

00:11:35.000 --> 00:11:36.000
Yes.

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:39.000
And what do you do after graduation?

00:11:39.000 --> 00:11:43.000
My older sister was in nursing school.

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:48.000
So I had to sit out of here until she graduated.

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:51.000
And what, do you remember the name of the school?

00:11:51.000 --> 00:11:55.000
Do you remember where she was going?

00:11:55.000 --> 00:12:00.000
The school was in Bibb County and Macon, Georgia, but I can't remember the name of it right now.

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:03.000
And so you had to stay out just because of the course?

00:12:03.000 --> 00:12:05.000
Yes.

00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:09.000
And so what did you do during that year?

00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:12.000
Baby said.

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:15.000
In the neighborhood or for your family?

00:12:15.000 --> 00:12:23.000
I had a customer across the street and sometimes she would break a smaller kid and I would keep them.

00:12:23.000 --> 00:12:26.000
I basically just kept house while my mother worked.

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:29.000
And your mother, what did she do?

00:12:29.000 --> 00:12:35.000
She worked, she did housekeeping works sometimes and then she worked at the high school.

00:12:35.000 --> 00:12:37.000
She was a cook.

00:12:37.000 --> 00:12:39.000
And this is in Sassar?

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:41.000
Yes.

00:12:41.000 --> 00:12:44.000
And so then your sister finished your sister program?

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:46.000
Yes.

00:12:46.000 --> 00:12:51.000
So now it's your turn to go to school and you choose to go to Albany State.

00:12:51.000 --> 00:12:54.000
Why did you choose all of these things?

00:12:54.000 --> 00:12:59.000
I, whatever I was born of, I was kind of a sickly child.

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:03.000
And my parents didn't want me to get too far away from me.

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:07.000
So they had a little bit of a say in that as well?

00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:09.000
Yes.

00:13:09.000 --> 00:13:12.000
But they wanted you to go to college?

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:13.000
Yes.

00:13:13.000 --> 00:13:15.000
What was their thinking behind that?

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:17.000
Did they ever share what you wanted?

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:19.000
They wanted me to be a teacher.

00:13:19.000 --> 00:13:23.000
They wanted me to go to the nursing school like my sister.

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:27.000
I had to do what they wanted me to do.

00:13:27.000 --> 00:13:30.000
Was that ever a discussion or was that just known?

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:31.000
That was known.

00:13:31.000 --> 00:13:34.000
This is what you will do.

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:38.000
No, why didn't they want you to be a teacher?

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:43.000
I had an instructor who was always telling me I needed what I needed today.

00:13:43.000 --> 00:13:47.000
So she told them that so they took it from that.

00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:52.000
So when you enroll at Albany State, 1960,

00:13:52.000 --> 00:13:56.000
it's with the intention of becoming a teacher.

00:13:56.000 --> 00:14:01.000
And so what do you, do you choose a major?

00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:06.000
I, for some reason decided I wanted to do science,

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:08.000
but I don't know why I did that.

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:10.000
I wasn't that good in science.

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:14.000
I just really wasn't sure as I could what I was going to do.

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:16.000
Really.

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:19.000
And did you stay on campus?

00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:20.000
Yes.

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:26.000
What was out like when you arrived in 1960, no longer living at home?

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:30.000
A lot of people.

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:32.000
But I enjoyed living on campus.

00:14:32.000 --> 00:14:33.000
I did.

00:14:33.000 --> 00:14:38.000
The only problem was the food.

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:39.000
Not good.

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:42.000
Food was no good.

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:45.000
I was getting hepatitis from the food.

00:14:45.000 --> 00:14:47.000
The food was bad.

00:14:47.000 --> 00:14:50.000
Was this something that students complained about?

00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:52.000
Oh, yes.

00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:53.000
Administration.

00:14:53.000 --> 00:14:55.000
Did it choose to do anything?

00:14:55.000 --> 00:14:57.000
No.

00:14:57.000 --> 00:15:00.000
It didn't seem to matter.

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:01.000
It wasn't good.

00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:04.000
It was prepared badly.

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:07.000
Well, I won't go into that.

00:15:07.000 --> 00:15:11.000
So what was from the student perspective?

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:18.000
I feel that the administration was the supportive of the students.

00:15:18.000 --> 00:15:23.000
What was your opinion about the administration?

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:25.000
The school as a whole?

00:15:25.000 --> 00:15:30.000
As far as academics were concerned, yes.

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:38.000
But it seemed like when it came to the food, I guess they're just like the dottation took out all of that.

00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:42.360
But food was not good.

00:15:42.360 --> 00:15:43.360
And I would eat it.

00:15:43.360 --> 00:15:45.860
And so I ended up becoming ill.

00:15:45.860 --> 00:15:49.860
Did you stay here?

00:15:49.860 --> 00:15:52.860
Did you have to go home?

00:15:52.860 --> 00:15:57.800
I ended up having to leave because I had problems with my stuff.

00:15:57.800 --> 00:15:59.440
So I had to leave.

00:15:59.440 --> 00:16:03.040
Now did you, but you wanted to come back?

00:16:03.040 --> 00:16:04.360
No, that was it.

00:16:04.360 --> 00:16:06.160
Oh, right.

00:16:06.160 --> 00:16:08.880
So that was 1962.

00:16:08.880 --> 00:16:09.720
1962.

00:16:09.720 --> 00:16:15.040
Now by then, you had, has you already become involved

00:16:15.040 --> 00:16:17.880
with civil rights activities?

00:16:17.880 --> 00:16:22.200
That was a march downtown.

00:16:25.880 --> 00:16:28.120
And I don't want to get into something

00:16:28.120 --> 00:16:31.680
I can't remember the full details.

00:16:31.680 --> 00:16:38.400
But it had to do with a young lady named Bertha Gober.

00:16:38.400 --> 00:16:40.040
And she's her name is the only one that

00:16:40.040 --> 00:16:42.920
comes to mind at this point.

00:16:42.920 --> 00:16:45.720
But we had a march downtown.

00:16:45.720 --> 00:16:48.200
And I was involved in it.

00:16:48.200 --> 00:16:53.120
Now, was she a home student here at Albany State?

00:16:53.120 --> 00:16:54.280
Yeah, of an estate.

00:16:57.160 --> 00:16:59.520
And has she been expelled?

00:16:59.520 --> 00:17:00.360
Do you recall?

00:17:03.920 --> 00:17:04.760
I can't remember.

00:17:04.760 --> 00:17:07.120
Now that was a long time ago.

00:17:07.120 --> 00:17:10.920
But you remember that that was, so the first time?

00:17:10.920 --> 00:17:11.960
The first time, yes.

00:17:11.960 --> 00:17:14.200
I participated in the march.

00:17:16.520 --> 00:17:17.560
What was that experience like?

00:17:17.560 --> 00:17:20.680
Do you remember just the experience of being on a march?

00:17:20.680 --> 00:17:24.080
Kind of scary, because I didn't know what was going to happen

00:17:24.080 --> 00:17:25.320
when we got downtown.

00:17:26.800 --> 00:17:28.400
Now did you march from campus?

00:17:29.400 --> 00:17:30.400
OK.

00:17:30.400 --> 00:17:33.920
How'd you hear about it?

00:17:33.920 --> 00:17:35.600
Different people talking about it.

00:17:35.600 --> 00:17:38.600
And they were going around and recruiting people

00:17:38.600 --> 00:17:39.440
to fly the march.

00:17:42.440 --> 00:17:44.000
But for some reason, I got involved.

00:17:44.000 --> 00:17:46.640
I thought, oh, wow, I just did.

00:17:46.640 --> 00:17:49.600
And so during the march, you say you're nervous,

00:17:49.600 --> 00:17:52.000
you're not going to show what's going to happen.

00:17:52.000 --> 00:17:53.880
No, no, no, what's going to happen downtown?

00:17:53.880 --> 00:17:54.960
You're fearful of the police?

00:17:54.960 --> 00:17:55.640
And you know what?

00:17:55.640 --> 00:17:58.080
My parents kind of say when they found out that I

00:17:58.080 --> 00:18:01.920
had participated in the march.

00:18:01.920 --> 00:18:04.040
So you survived that day?

00:18:04.040 --> 00:18:05.600
Yes.

00:18:05.600 --> 00:18:08.600
No violence, no arrest.

00:18:08.600 --> 00:18:10.880
You get back to the dorm.

00:18:10.880 --> 00:18:11.680
What do you think?

00:18:15.360 --> 00:18:16.320
I got away with that.

00:18:19.360 --> 00:18:25.040
But when my parents found out about it, they didn't get mad.

00:18:26.640 --> 00:18:34.240
Because by then, things had started to enter accounting.

00:18:34.240 --> 00:18:37.400
It's sort of out in the open.

00:18:37.400 --> 00:18:38.920
People were having meetings.

00:18:38.920 --> 00:18:41.840
And so after that, things stopped.

00:18:41.840 --> 00:18:43.600
And things just started opening up.

00:18:43.600 --> 00:18:45.880
And I got involved.

00:18:45.880 --> 00:18:49.280
So after the march, you're back at the dorm.

00:18:49.280 --> 00:18:54.280
Word reaches your parents from the parents of other students.

00:18:54.280 --> 00:18:55.280
Do you even know?

00:18:55.280 --> 00:18:58.240
I said, well, parents, people coming from Dawson

00:18:58.240 --> 00:19:00.320
and sassing to school here.

00:19:00.320 --> 00:19:05.000
And did they, was it ever even a conversation about it?

00:19:05.000 --> 00:19:06.840
About your participation at that time?

00:19:06.840 --> 00:19:11.080
The head cook at the school where my mother

00:19:11.080 --> 00:19:13.800
wrote, mentioning it to her.

00:19:13.800 --> 00:19:18.480
I know your daughter has better sense than to get involved

00:19:18.480 --> 00:19:19.760
in something like that.

00:19:19.760 --> 00:19:21.920
And she's also where she did it.

00:19:21.920 --> 00:19:22.920
And this is a white woman.

00:19:22.920 --> 00:19:24.840
She's here.

00:19:24.840 --> 00:19:27.520
And she did it.

00:19:27.520 --> 00:19:29.600
So that was the end of that.

00:19:29.600 --> 00:19:32.480
And did that head cook ever say anything else to her

00:19:32.480 --> 00:19:33.360
at that time?

00:19:33.360 --> 00:19:34.280
I don't know.

00:19:34.280 --> 00:19:35.960
If she mentioned it again.

00:19:40.160 --> 00:19:42.040
And so after that march, you participate.

00:19:42.040 --> 00:19:45.520
Your parents, hey, that's OK.

00:19:45.520 --> 00:19:47.560
That's OK.

00:19:47.560 --> 00:19:49.440
Do you still at Albany State?

00:19:49.440 --> 00:19:52.400
Did you haven't gotten sick yet?

00:19:52.400 --> 00:19:54.120
Do you get involved in other activities?

00:19:54.120 --> 00:19:55.520
Other marches and demonstrations?

00:19:55.520 --> 00:19:57.520
No, that was him.

00:19:57.520 --> 00:19:58.040
Why was that?

00:20:01.160 --> 00:20:03.120
I don't know.

00:20:03.120 --> 00:20:06.280
I just never got involved again here at the school.

00:20:06.280 --> 00:20:08.760
That was good.

00:20:08.760 --> 00:20:18.200
So the spring of 1962, you get sick.

00:20:18.200 --> 00:20:21.680
You head back home at that time.

00:20:21.680 --> 00:20:25.120
And you just recuperate at the house.

00:20:25.120 --> 00:20:26.800
Had you thought about what you're thinking that you were

00:20:26.800 --> 00:20:28.600
going to return to school?

00:20:28.600 --> 00:20:30.920
I thought about it.

00:20:30.920 --> 00:20:36.000
And then I got really and truly involved in the movement.

00:20:36.000 --> 00:20:39.920
And that doesn't work.

00:20:39.920 --> 00:20:40.600
And to go life.

00:20:40.600 --> 00:20:42.200
It's going to life with its own.

00:20:42.200 --> 00:20:46.200
So your back home, you recuperating.

00:20:46.200 --> 00:20:49.760
And things are starting to happen in terror.

00:20:49.760 --> 00:20:54.280
Now, how do you get involved in what's happening back home?

00:20:54.280 --> 00:20:59.160
Because when I got home, my parents were already involved.

00:20:59.160 --> 00:21:00.200
And what were they doing?

00:21:00.200 --> 00:21:01.840
You saying they were already involved?

00:21:01.840 --> 00:21:03.120
Going to meetings.

00:21:03.120 --> 00:21:08.840
They were having meetings at one of the churches in Dawson,

00:21:08.840 --> 00:21:09.360
I believe.

00:21:09.360 --> 00:21:13.640
It was the Zine Hill, a Sardis Baptist church.

00:21:13.640 --> 00:21:16.600
And they moved from there to my knowledge.

00:21:16.600 --> 00:21:18.000
OK.

00:21:18.000 --> 00:21:21.080
the meetings have moved from there to my home.

00:21:21.080 --> 00:21:23.720
And my knowledge was your family church.

00:21:23.720 --> 00:21:27.200
It was a family home.

00:21:27.200 --> 00:21:31.640
Were you starting to attend meetings as well?

00:21:31.640 --> 00:21:41.200
And the Terrell Movement, the Terrell Movement, the organization,

00:21:41.200 --> 00:21:45.560
when does that get started?

00:21:45.560 --> 00:21:52.040
When I got back home in 1962, I believe they started

00:21:52.040 --> 00:21:54.600
to get together in 1960.

00:21:54.600 --> 00:21:55.600
OK.

00:21:55.600 --> 00:21:58.360
They started to get, I didn't know anything about it.

00:21:58.360 --> 00:22:01.640
But it had started in 1960.

00:22:01.640 --> 00:22:04.000
And so how did you get involved with it?

00:22:04.000 --> 00:22:07.880
Because at certain point, you become secretary, correct?

00:22:07.880 --> 00:22:11.320
Out of left school, that's when I got really started getting

00:22:11.320 --> 00:22:12.000
involved.

00:22:12.000 --> 00:22:13.400
My parents were going to the meetings.

00:22:13.400 --> 00:22:14.720
So I started going with them.

00:22:14.720 --> 00:22:20.320
And the president of that movement, man's name,

00:22:20.320 --> 00:22:21.560
his name is Lucius Holloway.

00:22:24.440 --> 00:22:30.040
And I don't know how I got drawn into becoming the secretary,

00:22:30.040 --> 00:22:31.040
but I did.

00:22:31.040 --> 00:22:33.600
So there was no office to elect me.

00:22:33.600 --> 00:22:36.120
I did somehow gotten involved.

00:22:36.120 --> 00:22:39.440
Now, did you, you and your parents,

00:22:39.440 --> 00:22:42.440
while you were going to those mass meetings,

00:22:42.440 --> 00:22:43.640
were they talking to you?

00:22:43.640 --> 00:22:44.960
Were they talking among themselves?

00:22:44.960 --> 00:22:45.600
We talked.

00:22:45.600 --> 00:22:46.640
We talked about it.

00:22:46.640 --> 00:22:49.400
Whatever went on in the meetings, we discussed it.

00:22:49.400 --> 00:22:51.160
When we got home, we talked about it.

00:22:51.160 --> 00:22:55.920
And things that we needed to get done in the school systems

00:22:55.920 --> 00:22:56.920
and in the community.

00:22:56.920 --> 00:22:59.320
We wanted to become registered voters.

00:22:59.320 --> 00:23:02.720
So we went a couple of times trying to get registered.

00:23:02.720 --> 00:23:06.320
And the registrar would leave the office.

00:23:06.320 --> 00:23:08.400
And where was the registrar's office at the time?

00:23:08.400 --> 00:23:11.720
In the courthouse, in the basement of the courthouse.

00:23:11.720 --> 00:23:12.640
The kind of courthouse.

00:23:12.640 --> 00:23:15.840
And he was Santa Claus at the post office and washes.

00:23:18.400 --> 00:23:22.240
When we did catch him in his office,

00:23:22.240 --> 00:23:24.920
when we did let us become registered voters,

00:23:24.920 --> 00:23:28.920
we had to read a scripture from the Bible

00:23:31.080 --> 00:23:33.120
before we could fill out the form.

00:23:34.120 --> 00:23:38.640
And when did you finally get a chance to even fill out the form?

00:23:39.640 --> 00:23:43.640
I don't remember exactly the time and the date of that.

00:23:45.400 --> 00:23:47.840
But we did become registered voters.

00:23:49.040 --> 00:23:53.440
My mother lost such a job at the white school because of it.

00:23:53.440 --> 00:23:54.720
For having registered?

00:23:54.720 --> 00:23:56.640
Because we registered voters.

00:23:56.640 --> 00:23:58.240
Now, five here.

00:23:58.240 --> 00:24:01.280
Did that happen because she had actually successfully registered?

00:24:01.280 --> 00:24:02.600
Yes.

00:24:02.600 --> 00:24:05.520
So even before, I mean, so obviously they would keep in track.

00:24:05.520 --> 00:24:07.400
They would keep in divs on what she was doing.

00:24:07.400 --> 00:24:08.560
Yes.

00:24:08.800 --> 00:24:11.360
Not happy with her attending these mass meetings

00:24:11.360 --> 00:24:12.240
and her and her.

00:24:12.240 --> 00:24:17.240
Was she feeling pressure at the job before she was fired?

00:24:17.240 --> 00:24:20.720
They didn't pressure her to that point where,

00:24:20.720 --> 00:24:23.720
she would just want to leave, but they just out,

00:24:23.720 --> 00:24:25.200
I told her she had to go.

00:24:28.760 --> 00:24:30.560
None you could do about that at that point.

00:24:30.560 --> 00:24:33.040
I was telling her she had to go.

00:24:33.040 --> 00:24:36.840
So she went to Albany and she started doing housework.

00:24:36.840 --> 00:24:39.200
And they called her later that she was working for

00:24:39.200 --> 00:24:41.880
and tried to get the later to fire her.

00:24:41.880 --> 00:24:45.360
And she told, I don't have anything to do with it.

00:24:45.360 --> 00:24:47.400
She didn't care her counting.

00:24:47.400 --> 00:24:51.160
All I need her to do is to do what I ask her to do.

00:24:51.160 --> 00:24:52.000
And I pay.

00:24:53.200 --> 00:24:53.960
So she refused.

00:24:53.960 --> 00:24:56.960
You remember who that woman was and they abandoned you?

00:25:01.280 --> 00:25:03.480
When your mom, do you remember your mother coming home

00:25:03.480 --> 00:25:04.960
saying that she had been fired?

00:25:05.960 --> 00:25:08.280
From the from from from from Sassar.

00:25:13.280 --> 00:25:16.760
Kind of, it's kind of down, but, you know,

00:25:16.760 --> 00:25:23.520
it, we talked about it periodically.

00:25:23.520 --> 00:25:28.000
And they should we got fired out and we didn't remember that day.

00:25:28.000 --> 00:25:30.000
But you would talk about the fact that she had been.

00:25:30.000 --> 00:25:31.000
Yes.

00:25:31.000 --> 00:25:31.800
How does she feel about it?

00:25:35.800 --> 00:25:41.800
Well, how would anybody feel on that website.

00:25:41.800 --> 00:25:48.960
Not necessarily angry, but sort of disappointed in the way

00:25:48.960 --> 00:25:53.320
that it was done.

00:25:53.320 --> 00:25:58.880
You know, I have a right to become a registered voter.

00:25:58.880 --> 00:26:02.680
This is my God giving right.

00:26:02.680 --> 00:26:07.680
So why should you take it away from me?

00:26:07.680 --> 00:26:11.080
Well, that's what happened.

00:26:11.080 --> 00:26:12.280
Was there anything?

00:26:12.280 --> 00:26:17.680
Did that change at all the way your family was involved

00:26:17.680 --> 00:26:18.720
in the movement?

00:26:18.720 --> 00:26:21.720
No.

00:26:21.720 --> 00:26:23.040
Has made it even stronger?

00:26:28.960 --> 00:26:32.400
As Secretary of the Terrible Movement,

00:26:32.400 --> 00:26:35.880
what was some of the things that you did?

00:26:35.880 --> 00:26:42.280
I would take notes as to what was being said.

00:26:42.280 --> 00:26:44.960
Different people would come in and talk about the things

00:26:44.960 --> 00:26:48.880
that they had experienced on their jobs.

00:26:48.880 --> 00:26:50.720
The people from SNCC would come and they

00:26:50.720 --> 00:26:59.720
would talk in like Charles Sherrod, Don Steward, Prathia Hall.

00:26:59.720 --> 00:27:00.720
Prathia Hall Hall?

00:27:02.400 --> 00:27:06.880
Ralph Allen.

00:27:06.880 --> 00:27:11.120
And sometimes we would have reporters there.

00:27:11.120 --> 00:27:12.400
So is all of the mass meetings?

00:27:12.400 --> 00:27:14.360
Yes.

00:27:14.360 --> 00:27:19.760
And then from time to time, the police

00:27:19.760 --> 00:27:22.680
would press the music, Sheriff Z.T. Mathews, and his deputies

00:27:22.680 --> 00:27:26.800
would come and they would put their feet on the seats

00:27:26.800 --> 00:27:34.280
and just talk be ugly, really ugly.

00:27:34.280 --> 00:27:36.000
We would sickle this mess.

00:27:36.000 --> 00:27:38.840
They would say, I black people are doing fine.

00:27:38.840 --> 00:27:41.640
They're happy with things the way they are.

00:27:41.640 --> 00:27:44.360
And the outsiders are coming in and stirring up

00:27:44.360 --> 00:27:47.400
I black people and stuff like that.

00:27:47.400 --> 00:27:50.840
So they would physically show up at a mass meetings?

00:27:50.840 --> 00:27:52.040
Yes.

00:27:52.040 --> 00:27:53.840
Now when would a mass meetings tell?

00:27:53.840 --> 00:27:55.080
At Mount Olive.

00:27:55.080 --> 00:27:55.800
At Mount Olive.

00:27:55.800 --> 00:27:59.320
And there were Wednesdays or Sundays?

00:27:59.320 --> 00:28:01.400
I think the meetings I believe are not

00:28:01.400 --> 00:28:03.040
mistaken on a Wednesday night.

00:28:03.040 --> 00:28:05.280
I believe those.

00:28:05.280 --> 00:28:07.080
Each county saw a head there on night

00:28:07.080 --> 00:28:08.920
that they had that meetings.

00:28:08.920 --> 00:28:13.320
And the different counties would support each other.

00:28:13.320 --> 00:28:15.480
Like on Wednesday night, while chair of county

00:28:15.480 --> 00:28:17.240
was on Wednesday night, we would go to the county

00:28:17.240 --> 00:28:20.560
if there was on Tuesday night, back in football.

00:28:20.560 --> 00:28:22.960
About how many people would be at the mass meetings?

00:28:26.000 --> 00:28:28.600
Maybe 30 or 40, sometimes maybe less.

00:28:28.600 --> 00:28:29.440
It just depends.

00:28:33.600 --> 00:28:38.640
And when Sheriff Z.T. Mathews would show up, how would that,

00:28:38.640 --> 00:28:42.080
how would people respond?

00:28:42.080 --> 00:28:44.120
We would keep doing whatever we were doing.

00:28:44.120 --> 00:28:46.200
even with the singing, we would continue to sing.

00:28:46.200 --> 00:28:51.120
If one of the SNCC workers was up talking,

00:28:51.120 --> 00:28:55.440
speaking, they would just continue to speak.

00:28:55.440 --> 00:28:57.280
Do you sometimes they would interrupt?

00:28:57.280 --> 00:29:00.120
Yeah.

00:29:00.120 --> 00:29:08.040
Do you remember meeting SNCC workers for the first time?

00:29:08.040 --> 00:29:09.600
I'm trying to remember the first one.

00:29:09.600 --> 00:29:11.520
I mean, I was a linguist, Charles Sherrod.

00:29:11.520 --> 00:29:14.640
if I'm not mistaken.

00:29:14.640 --> 00:29:15.920
What do you think of them?

00:29:15.920 --> 00:29:19.520
Not the first time, but just as a whole?

00:29:19.520 --> 00:29:22.920
I thought he was a very unique person.

00:29:22.920 --> 00:29:27.160
He had a very sweet and common personality.

00:29:30.440 --> 00:29:31.680
Never raised his voice.

00:29:34.440 --> 00:29:36.520
Always to me, very sure of himself.

00:29:39.600 --> 00:29:40.880
I don't think he's still the same.

00:29:44.520 --> 00:29:48.880
How often were they in the county?

00:29:48.880 --> 00:29:50.440
Often.

00:29:50.440 --> 00:29:52.320
They were very visible.

00:29:52.320 --> 00:29:54.920
They were always around.

00:29:54.920 --> 00:29:57.440
Somebody, if it wasn't Sarrard, it was somebody

00:29:57.440 --> 00:29:58.720
of the SNCC workers.

00:29:58.720 --> 00:30:01.200
Somebody was always around.

00:30:01.200 --> 00:30:06.160
Now, were there, hey, SNCC workers staying in the county?

00:30:06.160 --> 00:30:06.960
Or were there most of them?

00:30:06.960 --> 00:30:07.560
That was a lady.

00:30:07.560 --> 00:30:09.640
Her name was Carolyn Daniels.

00:30:09.640 --> 00:30:12.800
And they were staying at her house.

00:30:12.800 --> 00:30:15.480
If I am not mistaken, Lucius Holloway

00:30:15.480 --> 00:30:17.240
would have some boy in his house.

00:30:20.000 --> 00:30:21.200
Nobody ever stayed with us.

00:30:21.200 --> 00:30:25.440
But my mother would make cakes and things of that for them.

00:30:25.440 --> 00:30:26.720
Try to get up to feed them.

00:30:26.720 --> 00:30:27.240
You know.

00:30:27.240 --> 00:30:27.760
Yeah.

00:30:29.880 --> 00:30:31.240
The voter registration activity.

00:30:31.240 --> 00:30:35.040
So yourself and your parents had gone down

00:30:35.040 --> 00:30:36.720
to attempt to register the vote.

00:30:36.720 --> 00:30:39.080
Did you do canvassing activities as well?

00:30:39.080 --> 00:30:39.920
Yes.

00:30:41.920 --> 00:30:47.880
Myself and some of the students from the high school,

00:30:47.880 --> 00:30:52.120
Gladys Clark, who was not deceased and his sister,

00:30:52.120 --> 00:30:58.280
Anadine Clark, we would canvas the areas in Dawson

00:30:58.280 --> 00:31:02.280
in the evenings after school going door to door.

00:31:02.280 --> 00:31:03.440
The people were running the house.

00:31:03.440 --> 00:31:04.520
One day, we'll see us coming.

00:31:04.520 --> 00:31:05.800
Here, come to Freedom Riders.

00:31:05.800 --> 00:31:06.960
That's what they called us.

00:31:06.960 --> 00:31:09.320
And they were going to house and clothes and do

00:31:09.320 --> 00:31:10.920
what they were afraid to talk to us.

00:31:10.920 --> 00:31:21.040
And those who didn't quite run or even those did,

00:31:21.040 --> 00:31:23.640
but those who you caught up with, what would you say?

00:31:25.640 --> 00:31:29.680
We were talking to them about becoming registered voters

00:31:29.680 --> 00:31:33.200
and trying to encourage them to come to the meeting

00:31:33.200 --> 00:31:36.160
so they could hear and see what was going on.

00:31:36.160 --> 00:31:41.400
But they were afraid of losing their jobs,

00:31:41.400 --> 00:31:43.120
of being made to move out of the home,

00:31:43.120 --> 00:31:46.080
but they were living in because they would be ranting.

00:31:46.080 --> 00:31:51.720
And they would just tell us, I'm afraid I get fired.

00:31:51.720 --> 00:31:53.040
I'll have to move.

00:31:53.040 --> 00:31:55.240
And that's the reason why they didn't want to be seen.

00:31:55.240 --> 00:31:56.840
They didn't want to be seen talking to us.

00:32:01.480 --> 00:32:05.920
How long would you spend out, canvassing, or an avid?

00:32:05.920 --> 00:32:10.360
The case would get out of about 3, 3, 30.

00:32:10.360 --> 00:32:13.280
And we would walk sometimes until we were starting to get dark.

00:32:17.480 --> 00:32:20.280
But then we would sometimes hitchhike.

00:32:20.280 --> 00:32:22.680
Just try to find a way home.

00:32:22.680 --> 00:32:26.000
Were you ever worried about your safety while you were out there?

00:32:26.000 --> 00:32:27.960
Oh, yes.

00:32:27.960 --> 00:32:31.160
We've been crazy not to.

00:32:31.160 --> 00:32:33.480
What were you concerned about?

00:32:36.480 --> 00:32:40.360
The life of what not happy about what we were doing.

00:32:40.360 --> 00:32:43.840
And that were threats.

00:32:43.840 --> 00:32:46.800
So we had to be careful.

00:32:46.800 --> 00:32:49.280
And being careful meant what?

00:32:49.280 --> 00:32:50.200
You watch your back.

00:32:53.200 --> 00:32:55.720
Any car come by, you move out of the road.

00:32:59.160 --> 00:33:02.600
So you didn't want to get here.

00:33:02.600 --> 00:33:05.920
And at some point, sometimes they will swing out of that.

00:33:05.920 --> 00:33:07.240
So you had to be careful.

00:33:07.240 --> 00:33:08.240
The cars.

00:33:08.240 --> 00:33:09.240
The cars will swing out of that.

00:33:15.320 --> 00:33:19.760
You would never canvas by yourself.

00:33:19.760 --> 00:33:20.680
No.

00:33:20.680 --> 00:33:21.920
So you would always pair up.

00:33:21.920 --> 00:33:22.680
You always had.

00:33:22.680 --> 00:33:26.320
That was always, but either 2 or 3 always together.

00:33:26.320 --> 00:33:27.560
You never go out by yourself.

00:33:28.000 --> 00:33:35.240
And the students, they were younger than you.

00:33:35.240 --> 00:33:36.240
Yes.

00:33:36.240 --> 00:33:39.640
So they were looking up to you.

00:33:39.640 --> 00:33:41.000
I don't know about that.

00:33:41.000 --> 00:33:42.360
They were always bigger than me.

00:33:42.360 --> 00:33:43.880
I was the smallest, not many groups.

00:33:43.880 --> 00:33:46.920
So I don't know if they were looking up to me or not.

00:33:46.920 --> 00:33:49.720
But I was always the smallest, not many groups.

00:33:49.720 --> 00:33:52.080
So I don't know about them looking up to me.

00:33:52.080 --> 00:33:58.520
But we all had the same goal as to help black people get what

00:33:58.520 --> 00:34:00.360
they were supposed to have, where they'd

00:34:00.360 --> 00:34:02.320
been taken away from us.

00:34:02.320 --> 00:34:06.200
That was our goal to become decent citizen, first class

00:34:06.200 --> 00:34:09.120
citizen.

00:34:09.120 --> 00:34:10.560
Well, some of the other activities

00:34:10.560 --> 00:34:17.400
that the Terracan movement was doing that you were involved in.

00:34:17.400 --> 00:34:19.680
Well, occasionally with Reverend Samuel Wells,

00:34:19.680 --> 00:34:23.640
we would do some city and sometimes.

00:34:23.640 --> 00:34:24.600
And who was this Reverend?

00:34:24.600 --> 00:34:25.320
Reverend Samuel Wells.

00:34:25.320 --> 00:34:26.640
His name was Reverend Samuel Wells.

00:34:26.640 --> 00:34:29.400
I think he passed on.

00:34:29.400 --> 00:34:30.880
And you would do some cities.

00:34:30.880 --> 00:34:33.440
To some cities.

00:34:33.440 --> 00:34:33.960
Where?

00:34:33.960 --> 00:34:36.880
We would just go into a restaurant.

00:34:36.880 --> 00:34:38.640
It was a restaurant in Dawson.

00:34:38.640 --> 00:34:41.640
I can't think of the name of it.

00:34:41.640 --> 00:34:45.800
And he would tell us what we were supposed to do before we went in.

00:34:45.800 --> 00:34:49.360
He said, we would just go and just sit at the counter.

00:34:49.360 --> 00:34:50.920
But just sit down.

00:34:50.920 --> 00:34:53.400
He said if they say something, we'll just leave.

00:34:53.400 --> 00:34:54.520
And that's what we would do.

00:34:54.520 --> 00:34:56.320
We said, I don't want anybody to get in trouble.

00:34:56.320 --> 00:34:59.200
And anybody to get hit in anything.

00:34:59.200 --> 00:35:02.480
He was sort of an objector.

00:35:02.480 --> 00:35:03.600
And you did that?

00:35:03.600 --> 00:35:04.600
We did.

00:35:04.600 --> 00:35:05.960
And what are we told us to do?

00:35:05.960 --> 00:35:07.760
That's what we did.

00:35:07.760 --> 00:35:13.640
Or else he wouldn't tell us anything that was going to get anybody hurt.

00:35:13.640 --> 00:35:17.000
What was it like going in to some of these places?

00:35:17.000 --> 00:35:18.920
It was scary.

00:35:18.920 --> 00:35:21.080
Always a little scary.

00:35:21.080 --> 00:35:25.120
But you never knew what was going to happen.

00:35:25.120 --> 00:35:27.840
Did anything ever happen?

00:35:27.840 --> 00:35:30.120
Well, you would get taught ugly too.

00:35:30.120 --> 00:35:31.000
Yeah.

00:35:31.000 --> 00:35:36.600
Called names by the patrons.

00:35:36.600 --> 00:35:37.720
Yeah, by the owners.

00:35:37.720 --> 00:35:39.400
By the owner, by the owners.

00:35:39.400 --> 00:35:43.560
Well, well, well, why the person that was working there,

00:35:43.560 --> 00:35:45.160
we don't serve you there.

00:35:45.160 --> 00:35:47.680
You hear so.

00:35:47.680 --> 00:35:49.000
But we just get up late.

00:35:49.000 --> 00:35:49.920
We were not going with.

00:35:49.920 --> 00:35:50.760
We just get up late.

00:35:54.600 --> 00:35:57.000
Did you ever have any runs with the police?

00:36:00.400 --> 00:36:04.960
You never ended running with police except at the church.

00:36:04.960 --> 00:36:05.960
When they would show up?

00:36:05.960 --> 00:36:06.600
When they would show up.

00:36:06.600 --> 00:36:07.560
At the mass meetings.

00:36:07.560 --> 00:36:08.080
Yes.

00:36:11.520 --> 00:36:12.840
So we have the mass meetings.

00:36:12.840 --> 00:36:14.840
You're doing voter registration work.

00:36:14.840 --> 00:36:17.240
You're doing these sit-ins.

00:36:17.240 --> 00:36:18.240
Other activities?

00:36:18.240 --> 00:36:20.240
Were there other things that you were doing as well?

00:36:23.600 --> 00:36:29.120
We had a after the church.

00:36:29.120 --> 00:36:31.480
After the church was burned.

00:36:31.480 --> 00:36:32.400
Oh, yes.

00:36:32.400 --> 00:36:33.320
Mount Olive Baptist Church.

00:36:33.320 --> 00:36:34.400
The series of churches.

00:36:34.400 --> 00:36:34.800
Yes.

00:36:34.800 --> 00:36:36.960
OK.

00:36:36.960 --> 00:36:42.160
We had, they started a school and a dope school.

00:36:42.160 --> 00:36:44.480
And they would teach us some of the doves

00:36:44.480 --> 00:36:49.480
that could not read and write how to write their names there

00:36:49.480 --> 00:36:52.000
for bands, things of that nature.

00:36:52.000 --> 00:36:54.680
And that's what I would go there.

00:36:54.680 --> 00:37:00.360
I wasn't a teacher, but I would attend those classes.

00:37:00.360 --> 00:37:02.120
So like adult literacy schools?

00:37:02.120 --> 00:37:03.560
Yes.

00:37:03.560 --> 00:37:07.280
And who were the people who were coming in?

00:37:07.280 --> 00:37:14.360
Some of the people's ADL sales, St. Robert,

00:37:14.360 --> 00:37:16.720
it's Catherine Mallory.

00:37:16.720 --> 00:37:17.760
They all now deceased.

00:37:20.760 --> 00:37:22.480
And it would be kind of fun.

00:37:22.480 --> 00:37:25.000
They enjoyed it.

00:37:25.000 --> 00:37:28.040
If they were learned to say they're alphabets

00:37:28.040 --> 00:37:31.000
and they could do them all the way through,

00:37:31.000 --> 00:37:32.560
it would be so funny to them.

00:37:32.560 --> 00:37:37.560
They're just rejoicing that they had learned to do this.

00:37:37.560 --> 00:37:42.440
And all their life, they hadn't been able to do it.

00:37:42.440 --> 00:37:46.360
Now, were they encouraged and registered a vote as well?

00:37:46.360 --> 00:37:49.760
They'd become registered a vote.

00:37:49.760 --> 00:37:50.920
And so that was part of it.

00:37:50.920 --> 00:37:52.560
That was part of the organ.

00:37:52.560 --> 00:37:53.080
We talked.

00:37:53.080 --> 00:37:55.600
We also talked them how to vote, what to do

00:37:55.600 --> 00:37:59.200
when they would go into the voting post.

00:37:59.200 --> 00:38:02.120
Now, would you carry some of the people down

00:38:02.120 --> 00:38:04.720
to the county court house?

00:38:04.720 --> 00:38:13.480
Usually, I was one of the poll watcher.

00:38:13.480 --> 00:38:16.720
When during the elections, I was one of the poll watcher.

00:38:16.720 --> 00:38:18.640
And what elections were these?

00:38:18.640 --> 00:38:20.600
What were the same?

00:38:20.600 --> 00:38:25.720
The local elections, the national elections.

00:38:25.720 --> 00:38:27.040
I would be a poll watcher.

00:38:27.040 --> 00:38:31.880
And I would help people who could not read it right.

00:38:31.880 --> 00:38:34.320
You had to sign a form to sign that you had the help.

00:38:34.320 --> 00:38:36.600
These people had to sign the form.

00:38:36.600 --> 00:38:40.480
Then I would help them to call the names out to them

00:38:40.480 --> 00:38:42.880
and let them choose the one that they wanted to vote for.

00:38:42.880 --> 00:38:45.440
So this is even 1964.

00:38:45.440 --> 00:38:47.560
And they're done in the 60s.

00:38:47.560 --> 00:38:51.400
So you're standing in your poll watcher meeting

00:38:51.400 --> 00:38:52.920
that you're in a poll.

00:38:52.920 --> 00:38:56.040
And you're watching really basically what's going on.

00:38:56.040 --> 00:39:02.520
If anybody tried to keep people from voting basically.

00:39:02.520 --> 00:39:08.280
Did you ever have to intervene or on behalf of somebody?

00:39:08.280 --> 00:39:11.600
Not really.

00:39:11.600 --> 00:39:14.640
Because the federal government was in a federal people

00:39:14.640 --> 00:39:17.800
right here.

00:39:17.800 --> 00:39:21.720
I want to go back to late summer 62.

00:39:21.720 --> 00:39:26.080
You have been involved with the total movement.

00:39:26.080 --> 00:39:30.120
And the mass meetings had been being held at Mount Olive Baptist Church

00:39:30.120 --> 00:39:31.960
of the family church.

00:39:31.960 --> 00:39:36.480
And then in August, the church is burned.

00:39:36.480 --> 00:39:38.880
Yes.

00:39:38.880 --> 00:39:42.320
Could you tell me about that?

00:39:42.320 --> 00:39:48.360
It was like a death that someone you love had died.

00:39:48.360 --> 00:40:00.840
I said to think that people would be so mean that they

00:40:00.840 --> 00:40:04.160
were burned for church.

00:40:04.160 --> 00:40:07.680
It didn't stop anything.

00:40:07.680 --> 00:40:08.920
It's made us more determined.

00:40:13.400 --> 00:40:16.360
How could you burn a house of God?

00:40:16.360 --> 00:40:21.440
Because people will want to register to vote.

00:40:21.440 --> 00:40:22.120
That's what happened.

00:40:28.680 --> 00:40:34.320
What were some of the discussions after work?

00:40:34.320 --> 00:40:37.480
Well, people wondering who did it, why they did it.

00:40:40.840 --> 00:40:42.080
We're done in the middle of the night.

00:40:42.080 --> 00:40:44.360
So nobody knew.

00:40:44.360 --> 00:40:48.920
And I don't know if the U.S. Department of Justice

00:40:48.920 --> 00:40:52.200
ever found out who did it.

00:40:52.200 --> 00:40:57.240
Was there any speculation about who may have done it?

00:40:57.240 --> 00:40:58.720
They just said the white folks did it.

00:41:03.120 --> 00:41:04.040
So who did it?

00:41:04.040 --> 00:41:04.560
I don't know.

00:41:08.960 --> 00:41:10.720
Where did the mass meetings go afterward?

00:41:11.680 --> 00:41:13.680
I'm not mistaken.

00:41:13.680 --> 00:41:19.800
We went to the Methodist Church.

00:41:19.800 --> 00:41:22.120
They became afraid that they were going to burn their church.

00:41:22.120 --> 00:41:25.040
So they stopped us from doing that.

00:41:25.040 --> 00:41:32.000
By this time, they had started the foundation

00:41:32.000 --> 00:41:34.800
to reveal my dollar.

00:41:34.800 --> 00:41:36.040
We would put chairs there.

00:41:36.040 --> 00:41:39.040
And so they told us we could not do that.

00:41:39.040 --> 00:41:44.080
So then they brought in a big tent and put it in the back.

00:41:44.080 --> 00:41:48.440
And we held our son to services.

00:41:48.440 --> 00:41:50.640
And our meetings in that tent.

00:41:50.640 --> 00:41:52.960
Behind the foundation.

00:41:52.960 --> 00:41:54.920
The foundation as that was going on.

00:41:54.920 --> 00:41:59.360
Your brother was working with help to build that.

00:41:59.360 --> 00:42:02.160
Do you remember how your father reacted?

00:42:02.160 --> 00:42:04.880
To yous.

00:42:04.880 --> 00:42:09.000
And he said some words that wasn't Christian.

00:42:09.000 --> 00:42:12.200
Did I hold it?

00:42:12.200 --> 00:42:12.640
How about you?

00:42:12.640 --> 00:42:16.080
How about your mother?

00:42:16.080 --> 00:42:17.720
Sam.

00:42:17.720 --> 00:42:18.480
Everybody.

00:42:18.480 --> 00:42:20.520
It was just a sad day.

00:42:20.520 --> 00:42:24.040
As I said, it was just like a death.

00:42:24.040 --> 00:42:27.640
Because that church had always been there.

00:42:27.640 --> 00:42:33.120
It had always been a part of that little city in Terracan.

00:42:34.880 --> 00:42:44.120
And you mentioned that when you were canvassing, that you had to be careful.

00:42:44.120 --> 00:42:47.800
And now the church has been burned.

00:42:47.800 --> 00:42:52.080
Your family, your mother loses her job.

00:42:52.080 --> 00:42:56.320
Were you ever, was the family ever feel like they were in danger?

00:42:56.320 --> 00:42:57.320
Yes.

00:42:57.320 --> 00:42:59.320
Because the word was out.

00:42:59.320 --> 00:43:04.800
That anyone who participated in the meetings and they all know how things got burned.

00:43:04.800 --> 00:43:06.560
And they were in the homes.

00:43:06.560 --> 00:43:15.720
So we would take turns sitting up at night and watch it.

00:43:15.720 --> 00:43:21.080
To make sure nobody suspicious cars, were you looking for vehicles?

00:43:21.080 --> 00:43:25.320
Anyone trying to set a fire?

00:43:25.320 --> 00:43:31.800
Are any strange cars pulling in the yard and the, whatever?

00:43:31.800 --> 00:43:38.640
And as you saw somebody, what was the plan?

00:43:38.640 --> 00:43:45.920
Get everybody up out of the house.

00:43:45.920 --> 00:43:50.560
Escape before anything could happen.

00:43:50.560 --> 00:43:57.880
Now you have family members outside, I mean, in the community.

00:43:57.880 --> 00:43:58.800
Relatives.

00:43:58.800 --> 00:43:59.800
Yes.

00:43:59.800 --> 00:44:01.800
But they also active.

00:44:01.800 --> 00:44:05.120
And one uncle.

00:44:05.120 --> 00:44:09.440
My father's brother, he was also active.

00:44:09.440 --> 00:44:11.440
But some of the others weren't.

00:44:11.440 --> 00:44:16.880
Didn't have too many family members around.

00:44:16.880 --> 00:44:21.880
Around in the, in that area.

00:44:21.880 --> 00:44:24.520
How about some of your friends when you have become involved?

00:44:24.520 --> 00:44:28.360
Did they, did they also become involved when you had moved back home?

00:44:28.360 --> 00:44:31.880
My classmate is pretty much.

00:44:31.880 --> 00:44:33.800
Why, why, why was that?

00:44:33.800 --> 00:44:35.240
I have no idea.

00:44:38.480 --> 00:44:40.600
Did they treat you any differently?

00:44:40.600 --> 00:44:41.600
No.

00:44:45.200 --> 00:44:47.680
They just let you do your thing.

00:44:47.680 --> 00:44:50.840
I guess so.

00:44:50.840 --> 00:44:57.280
Most of my classmates when I came back, you know how little small towns, they have no jobs.

00:44:57.280 --> 00:45:01.480
So you go away to school, you don't come back.

00:45:01.480 --> 00:45:07.560
So a lot of them, they say what they were going for.

00:45:07.560 --> 00:45:13.960
So after the tragedy at Manawa, what is the movement do then?

00:45:19.320 --> 00:45:26.760
There were people from the U.S. Department of Justice that came down.

00:45:26.760 --> 00:45:29.680
We had, well the Georgia Bureau of Investigation's came first.

00:45:29.680 --> 00:45:32.000
The Georgia Bureau of Investigation.

00:45:32.000 --> 00:45:38.680
Not, in my opinion, not to try and find out who did what.

00:45:38.680 --> 00:45:45.680
But basically, I think just to cover them, say those.

00:45:45.680 --> 00:45:51.920
But when the U.S. Department of Justice came down, a lot of things started happening.

00:45:51.920 --> 00:45:56.560
They were taking statements from different people.

00:45:56.560 --> 00:46:03.080
And they took that back to Washington, with them.

00:46:03.080 --> 00:46:05.360
The little book that I had that I kept no sense.

00:46:05.360 --> 00:46:07.360
They took it back.

00:46:07.360 --> 00:46:09.440
I never got it back.

00:46:09.440 --> 00:46:11.360
And what's this little book?

00:46:11.360 --> 00:46:12.360
What is that?

00:46:12.360 --> 00:46:16.680
That's a little book that I just was scribbling little notes in.

00:46:16.680 --> 00:46:24.560
I was afraid to write down certain stuff because I didn't know who was going to get

00:46:24.560 --> 00:46:25.560
the hands on it.

00:46:25.560 --> 00:46:29.680
So I would just scribble certain stuff down.

00:46:29.680 --> 00:46:32.280
Was this sort of a notebook as you would take a meeting?

00:46:32.280 --> 00:46:33.280
Yes.

00:46:33.280 --> 00:46:35.280
You would take a meeting as a note from the meeting.

00:46:35.280 --> 00:46:39.080
So the U.S. Department of Justice, the investigator, the interviewer.

00:46:39.080 --> 00:46:40.080
The interviewer.

00:46:40.080 --> 00:46:41.080
Yes.

00:46:41.080 --> 00:46:43.080
What was that like?

00:46:43.080 --> 00:46:44.080
Like this one.

00:46:44.080 --> 00:46:45.080
And you just shared.

00:46:45.080 --> 00:46:46.080
We talked.

00:46:46.080 --> 00:46:47.080
Yeah.

00:46:47.080 --> 00:46:48.080
Did you think that we were going to do anything?

00:46:48.080 --> 00:46:49.080
Yes.

00:46:49.080 --> 00:46:50.080
Yes.

00:46:50.080 --> 00:46:51.080
What was that like?

00:46:51.080 --> 00:46:52.080
Like this one.

00:46:52.080 --> 00:46:53.080
And you just shared.

00:46:53.080 --> 00:46:54.080
We talked.

00:46:54.080 --> 00:46:57.120
Did you think that we were going to do anything?

00:46:57.120 --> 00:47:00.400
I kind of felt like they were.

00:47:00.400 --> 00:47:12.880
After then, people in Sasser had to go to Americus to federal court.

00:47:12.880 --> 00:47:17.280
As part of a court case, or what would they do?

00:47:17.280 --> 00:47:26.280
Many things that had happened in the area, the shooting at the SNCC workers, the local

00:47:26.280 --> 00:47:30.080
police officer that we had, were shooting at the SNCC workers.

00:47:30.080 --> 00:47:35.240
A whole lot of other stuff.

00:47:35.240 --> 00:47:45.720
With the burning of the churches in that area, they had to go to federal court.

00:47:45.720 --> 00:47:47.360
The shooting at the SNCC workers.

00:47:47.360 --> 00:47:53.560
As they were canvassing, was that something that was common?

00:47:53.560 --> 00:47:55.160
No, I don't know.

00:47:55.160 --> 00:48:02.280
I think the local police officer let somebody put something in his head that was right.

00:48:02.280 --> 00:48:07.160
And he believed it.

00:48:07.160 --> 00:48:08.160
So he was taking his act.

00:48:08.160 --> 00:48:14.640
He was doing what he thought he was supposed to do.

00:48:14.640 --> 00:48:19.840
Tell Counties, some people called it.

00:48:19.840 --> 00:48:20.840
Terrell County.

00:48:20.840 --> 00:48:23.320
Terrell County, it was.

00:48:23.320 --> 00:48:25.920
You think that was inappropriate?

00:48:25.920 --> 00:48:26.920
Why terrible?

00:48:26.920 --> 00:48:27.920
Why terrible?

00:48:27.920 --> 00:48:28.920
Because it was.

00:48:28.920 --> 00:48:30.920
It was just.

00:48:30.920 --> 00:48:43.160
I never run into really when I was growing up a whole lot of prejudice from the people because

00:48:43.160 --> 00:48:47.080
my parents protected us from that.

00:48:47.080 --> 00:48:50.160
We never worked in White folks' houses.

00:48:50.160 --> 00:48:51.160
When?

00:48:51.160 --> 00:48:54.320
Places of that nature.

00:48:54.320 --> 00:48:57.040
We were always protected from that.

00:48:57.040 --> 00:49:04.560
So some of the stuff that some people experienced, we never did.

00:49:04.560 --> 00:49:10.000
My worst experience was when I started working with the movement.

00:49:10.000 --> 00:49:11.600
Worst experience with White folks?

00:49:11.600 --> 00:49:21.440
Other than that, when I was a child, I didn't know.

00:49:21.440 --> 00:49:30.240
I knew that things they had was better than what I had with the special with the school.

00:49:30.240 --> 00:49:31.560
We had to walk school.

00:49:31.560 --> 00:49:34.320
They rode the school bus.

00:49:34.320 --> 00:49:37.920
They had better books.

00:49:37.920 --> 00:49:50.080
So that was really basically all in certain places that they could go that I couldn't go.

00:49:50.080 --> 00:49:53.360
But then they had the places for the blocks.

00:49:53.360 --> 00:49:58.640
So in a way, I felt like that was the way it counted, the way it was supposed to be.

00:49:58.640 --> 00:50:00.120
I still had some places to go.

00:50:00.120 --> 00:50:05.480
I may not have been able to go where they went, but we still have places to go.

00:50:05.480 --> 00:50:07.480
So did when you joined it.

00:50:07.480 --> 00:50:12.240
Back to the movement and now you're encountering and experiencing these white folks in this

00:50:12.240 --> 00:50:16.080
sort of different way, did that change what you thought about them?

00:50:16.080 --> 00:50:19.760
I'm seeing now what I've been missing.

00:50:19.760 --> 00:50:25.720
You know, you couldn't go into a restaurant and sit down and eat.

00:50:25.720 --> 00:50:31.880
If you went to get a hamburger, you had to get it through the hole in the wall because

00:50:31.880 --> 00:50:35.520
you couldn't go inside.

00:50:35.520 --> 00:50:43.800
So it kind of opened my eyes into what was really going on.

00:50:43.800 --> 00:50:52.360
And how that revelation, that opening your eyes, what did you make of it all?

00:50:52.360 --> 00:51:01.960
It made me determined to try to make things better for everybody, not just black people,

00:51:01.960 --> 00:51:06.080
but for everybody.

00:51:06.080 --> 00:51:11.120
Because you can't help one of this, you have the other.

00:51:11.120 --> 00:51:16.320
That would prove why people living in that area was, I would say just as poor as I was

00:51:16.320 --> 00:51:18.000
a poor.

00:51:18.000 --> 00:51:29.400
So you can't help one race of people unless you have the other race.

00:51:29.400 --> 00:51:32.960
Because the movement continued.

00:51:32.960 --> 00:51:36.200
So into 63 and 64.

00:51:36.200 --> 00:51:41.320
Did the kinds of things that you were doing change?

00:51:41.320 --> 00:51:45.960
Kind of slowed down a bit.

00:51:45.960 --> 00:51:51.080
When people became, started to become registered voters, things kind of, the canvass and kind

00:51:51.080 --> 00:51:53.640
of slowed down a bit.

00:51:53.640 --> 00:51:57.240
Most of it was done when people were running for elections.

00:51:57.240 --> 00:52:04.360
And when we started camps in the area trying to support this person, to support that person,

00:52:04.360 --> 00:52:07.720
get people out to the polls.

00:52:07.720 --> 00:52:11.560
Make sure that nobody kept them from voting.

00:52:11.560 --> 00:52:21.520
And they just, somewhere I in there, I stopped.

00:52:21.520 --> 00:52:25.400
I went home to take care of my sister's baby.

00:52:25.400 --> 00:52:27.840
She had a child and she was working.

00:52:27.840 --> 00:52:31.080
She needed somebody to keep so my parents brought me home.

00:52:31.080 --> 00:52:32.880
So that's what I was doing.

00:52:32.880 --> 00:52:38.040
And then later on I got married and I moved away.

00:52:38.040 --> 00:52:40.720
And when did you get?

00:52:40.720 --> 00:52:42.360
1967.

00:52:42.360 --> 00:52:44.960
And then where do you move to?

00:52:44.960 --> 00:52:46.240
Topeka, Kansas.

00:52:46.240 --> 00:52:47.960
Topeka, Kansas.

00:52:47.960 --> 00:52:51.680
I mean, so you move far.

00:52:51.680 --> 00:52:54.960
And this is your first time really away from poll?

00:52:54.960 --> 00:52:56.560
That far away from poll?

00:52:56.560 --> 00:52:57.560
That far away from poll?

00:52:57.560 --> 00:53:01.520
Was that, how was that experience for the leaving terrible behind?

00:53:01.520 --> 00:53:03.120
Wonderful experience.

00:53:03.120 --> 00:53:04.120
Wonderful.

00:53:04.120 --> 00:53:09.200
And a chance to travel to see some things, you know, see other places.

00:53:09.200 --> 00:53:13.200
It was fun.

00:53:13.200 --> 00:53:17.680
Did you stay in Kansas for long?

00:53:17.680 --> 00:53:18.680
Came back to Atlanta.

00:53:18.680 --> 00:53:19.680
To Atlanta.

00:53:19.680 --> 00:53:26.200
And I lived there for a while, but four years.

00:53:26.200 --> 00:53:29.800
Then I came back to Albany and went to work at Phoebe Putney.

00:53:29.800 --> 00:53:30.800
At the medical.

00:53:30.800 --> 00:53:31.600
At the hospital?

00:53:31.600 --> 00:53:34.280
Yes.

00:53:34.280 --> 00:53:36.640
And what were you doing at the hospital?

00:53:36.640 --> 00:53:41.400
Working in the CNA, Citiburn nursing system.

00:53:41.400 --> 00:53:49.480
How had the area changed if at all when you came back?

00:53:49.480 --> 00:53:53.520
Some places I didn't recognize.

00:53:53.520 --> 00:53:55.560
The black and white signs were down.

00:53:58.680 --> 00:54:02.560
You know, the black water fountain, the white water fountain.

00:54:02.560 --> 00:54:04.320
The signs were down.

00:54:04.320 --> 00:54:06.520
It was kind of strange, you know?

00:54:09.320 --> 00:54:10.680
I changed a lot.

00:54:10.680 --> 00:54:14.800
Then you could go into any restaurant you wanted to sit down.

00:54:14.800 --> 00:54:16.080
You could go to a movie and then you

00:54:16.080 --> 00:54:21.320
had to sit in the back and sit down on the lower level.

00:54:21.320 --> 00:54:23.160
And now people throw things out on you.

00:54:23.160 --> 00:54:25.680
So it was a lot different.

00:54:29.800 --> 00:54:32.000
Were you glad to be back?

00:54:32.000 --> 00:54:34.000
Yes.

00:54:34.000 --> 00:54:34.880
Did you stay?

00:54:34.880 --> 00:54:36.520
Did you live in Albany?

00:54:36.520 --> 00:54:37.640
Or were you living in?

00:54:37.640 --> 00:54:38.640
But my parents.

00:54:38.640 --> 00:54:41.480
I lived back in with my parents.

00:54:41.480 --> 00:54:46.880
And how Terrell was different.

00:54:46.880 --> 00:54:47.640
It was different.

00:54:47.640 --> 00:54:49.280
The schools were integrated.

00:54:53.680 --> 00:54:55.600
It was all about it.

00:54:55.600 --> 00:54:56.600
It was all about it.

00:54:56.600 --> 00:54:58.160
Everybody was riding the school bus.

00:54:58.160 --> 00:54:58.840
It's a school.

00:54:58.840 --> 00:55:01.520
So nobody walked into school anymore.

00:55:01.520 --> 00:55:03.480
It was all about it.

00:55:03.480 --> 00:55:09.600
Did you ever resume sort of movement type activities?

00:55:09.600 --> 00:55:10.400
Yes.

00:55:10.400 --> 00:55:12.600
I started working with NAACP.

00:55:12.600 --> 00:55:17.120
I became a deputy registrar.

00:55:17.120 --> 00:55:22.280
In 1979, I think I did that until 1996.

00:55:22.280 --> 00:55:28.200
Whatever year the voting started to where you could vote,

00:55:28.200 --> 00:55:30.680
could register to vote in any place, like whatever.

00:55:30.680 --> 00:55:33.360
That's when I basically saw that.

00:55:33.360 --> 00:55:37.680
I would do four hours on Saturday morning.

00:55:37.680 --> 00:55:38.760
Registering people to vote?

00:55:38.760 --> 00:55:40.280
Yes.

00:55:41.240 --> 00:55:46.040
So the movement kind of stayed with you.

00:55:46.040 --> 00:55:47.680
Why do you think that was the case?

00:55:50.720 --> 00:55:54.040
I guess the people thought I was dependable.

00:55:54.040 --> 00:55:54.880
So people would come out?

00:55:54.880 --> 00:55:56.120
They always call me.

00:55:56.120 --> 00:55:58.360
People who were in charge of what it was going on,

00:55:58.360 --> 00:56:01.840
would always call me so.

00:56:01.840 --> 00:56:05.360
Was the NAACP very strong?

00:56:05.360 --> 00:56:06.360
It was.

00:56:06.360 --> 00:56:07.720
Is it the Tereo County NAACP?

00:56:07.720 --> 00:56:08.240
Yes.

00:56:08.240 --> 00:56:09.560
OK.

00:56:09.560 --> 00:56:11.240
Not as strong as it used to be.

00:56:14.560 --> 00:56:17.560
Was that the main movement organization, if you will?

00:56:17.560 --> 00:56:21.280
The main center sort of movement activity in the 80s, 80s, 90s?

00:56:21.280 --> 00:56:23.640
Yeah, I believe so.

00:56:23.640 --> 00:56:26.560
You recall what the branch president was?

00:56:26.560 --> 00:56:27.800
JL Barnes.

00:56:27.800 --> 00:56:31.160
JL Barnes?

00:56:31.160 --> 00:56:32.520
He was a murder.

00:56:32.520 --> 00:56:33.560
He was murdered?

00:56:33.560 --> 00:56:34.560
No, I had.

00:56:37.360 --> 00:56:38.360
1994.

00:56:40.280 --> 00:56:45.240
Did he have anything to do with his activism?

00:56:50.040 --> 00:56:50.760
I believe so.

00:56:56.360 --> 00:57:05.760
So the danger for speaking out for being active didn't just

00:57:05.760 --> 00:57:07.720
go away in the 60s?

00:57:07.720 --> 00:57:07.920
No.

00:57:09.560 --> 00:57:19.560
So that's one of the things that didn't change.

00:57:19.560 --> 00:57:21.560
What do you say?

00:57:21.560 --> 00:57:25.560
Is this idea that there were people who were opposed to change?

00:57:28.560 --> 00:57:37.560
I don't know how to put this, but things are better.

00:57:39.560 --> 00:57:44.560
They look good.

00:57:44.560 --> 00:57:51.560
But there's a lot that needs to be worked on.

00:57:51.560 --> 00:57:55.560
You know, I stuff this under the cover.

00:57:55.560 --> 00:58:01.560
And you see the smiles and the handshakes.

00:58:01.560 --> 00:58:02.560
And.

00:58:03.560 --> 00:58:09.560
But everything is not coming up roses.

00:58:09.560 --> 00:58:15.560
And I don't think it ever will be.

00:58:15.560 --> 00:58:23.800
So what you have to do is just you do the best you can to make your life for you and

00:58:23.800 --> 00:58:30.560
your family and other people around you as comfortable as possible.

00:58:30.560 --> 00:58:35.560
You do what you can.

00:58:35.560 --> 00:58:50.560
Because I don't think we as black people are going to be where God intended for us to be.

00:58:50.560 --> 00:58:56.560
Because now people who are working every day to keep it from happening.

00:58:56.560 --> 00:59:01.560
You got a black president.

00:59:01.560 --> 00:59:06.560
And they're blocking him and every move he makes.

00:59:06.560 --> 00:59:15.560
So if he can't make things better, they won't let him or what you think about me.

00:59:15.560 --> 00:59:20.560
They're not going to listen to me either.

00:59:20.560 --> 00:59:30.560
But I try.

00:59:30.560 --> 00:59:35.560
We've covered we've covered a lot.

00:59:35.560 --> 00:59:39.560
But I know there's so much more that we could possibly talk about.

00:59:39.560 --> 00:59:48.560
Is there anything that you want to add that we pass we didn't talk about or you want to add say a little more about?

00:59:48.560 --> 00:59:56.560
Just ask our people to become more active in voting.

00:59:56.560 --> 01:00:01.560
Register to vote and voting after you register.

01:00:01.560 --> 01:00:11.560
Support your elected officials and whatever they're doing because it's for your benefit.

01:00:11.560 --> 01:00:15.560
We put them in office and then we hands off.

01:00:15.560 --> 01:00:18.560
They need to be held accountable.

01:00:18.560 --> 01:00:25.560
And if we don't do it, who's going to?

01:00:25.560 --> 01:00:28.560
That's valuable advice.

01:00:28.560 --> 01:00:32.560
Thank you so much.

01:00:32.560 --> 01:00:38.560
Thank you.

01:00:38.560 --> 01:00:48.560
This has been a presentation of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

